
## Diagram 1: Infrastructure Connectivity (Low-Level Design)

**Design Rationale:** This diagram maps the physical and logical network path from on-premises into Azure. The flow reads top-to-bottom: on-prem → ExpressRoute → Hub VNet → Spoke VNet peering → the three subnets. Private Endpoints are shown as lateral connections from the AKS subnet to their respective PaaS services, reinforcing the "no public endpoint" constraint. The three subnets are represented as flat peer nodes within a subgraph to avoid deep nesting while still communicating containment.

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph OnPrem["On-Premises Network"]
        DC[Corporate Data Centre]
        CB_AGENTS[CloudBees Agent Pool]
        VDI[VDI Jump Hosts]
    end

    subgraph Hub["Azure Hub VNet"]
        ER_GW[ExpressRoute Gateway]
        HUB_FW[Azure Firewall / Hub Router]
    end

    subgraph Spoke["AKS Spoke VNet - newzealandnorth"]
        SN_HUB[Hub-Connected Subnet]
        SN_AKS[AKS Node Subnet]
        SN_PE[Private Endpoint Subnet]
    end

    subgraph PaaS["Azure PaaS Services - Private"]
        AKV[Azure Key Vault]
        ACR[Azure Container Registry]
        SFTP[Azure Storage - SFTP]
        PG_VMs[PostgreSQL Azure VMs x3]
    end

    DC -->|ExpressRoute Circuit| ER_GW
    CB_AGENTS -->|ExpressRoute Circuit| ER_GW
    VDI -->|ExpressRoute Circuit| ER_GW
    ER_GW --> HUB_FW
    HUB_FW -->|VNet Peering| SN_HUB
    SN_HUB --> SN_AKS
    SN_HUB --> SN_PE
    SN_AKS -->|AKS Node Traffic| SN_PE
    SN_PE -->|Private Endpoint| AKV
    SN_PE -->|Private Endpoint| ACR
    SN_PE -->|Private Endpoint| SFTP
    SN_AKS -->|VM NIC - Internal| PG_VMs
```

