## Diagram 2: Management & Control Plane (High-Level Design)

**Design Rationale:** This diagram separates two distinct access patterns — **human access** and **automation access** — into clearly distinguishable flows. Current-state paths are shown as standard arrows. Target-state paths (direct kubectl via VDI) are annotated inline. The CloudBees automation path shows the full pipeline chain: Stash → Agent → proxy/ER → AKS API and registry targets. On-prem dependencies (Venafi, TFE) are shown as lateral calls from CloudBees to reinforce that they never leave the on-prem boundary.

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph HumanAccess["Human Access Paths"]
        LAPTOP[Admin Laptop - SSO]
        VDI[VDI Jump Host]
        PORTAL[Azure Portal - Read Only]
    end

    subgraph AutomationAccess["Automation - CloudBees Pipeline"]
        STASH[Stash On-Prem SCM]
        CB[CloudBees Agent - On-Prem]
        TFE[TF Enterprise Registry - On-Prem]
        VENAFI[Venafi CA - On-Prem]
    end

    subgraph AzureTargets["Azure Targets - newzealandnorth"]
        AKS_API[AKS Private API Server]
        ACR[Azure Container Registry]
        AKV[Azure Key Vault]
        STORAGE[Azure Storage - SFTP]
    end

    LAPTOP -->|SSO - Read Only| PORTAL
    LAPTOP -->|RDP / Citrix| VDI
    VDI -->|kubectl - Target State via ExpressRoute| AKS_API

    STASH -->|Webhook Trigger| CB
    CB -->|Terraform Apply via Proxy / ExpressRoute| AKS_API
    CB -->|Docker Push via Proxy / ExpressRoute| ACR
    CB -->|Request TLS Cert| VENAFI
    CB -->|Source Modules| TFE
    CB -->|Read Secrets| AKV
    CB -->|Artifact Transfer| STORAGE
```

