## Diagram 4: Security AAA & Secrets Flow (Sequence Diagram)

**Design Rationale:** This uses `sequenceDiagram` syntax, which is the clearest format for a multi-actor authentication handshake. The sequence faithfully models the Workload Identity + Secrets Store CSI Driver flow: the pod first exchanges its projected Service Account token with Entra ID for a scoped JWT, then presents that JWT to Azure Key Vault via the CSI driver. The secret is never passed through the application directly — it is mounted as an in-memory volume file, reinforcing the least-privilege principle. Notes are used to annotate the key trust boundary.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    autonumber
    participant Pod as App Pod
    participant K8s as Kubernetes API
    participant Entra as Entra ID (OIDC)
    participant CSI as Secrets Store CSI Driver
    participant AKV as Azure Key Vault

    Pod->>K8s: Mount projected Service Account token
    K8s-->>Pod: Projected JWT (short-lived, audience-scoped)

    Note over Pod,Entra: Workload Identity Token Exchange

    Pod->>Entra: POST /token (projected JWT + client assertion)
    Entra-->>Pod: Azure AD access token (scoped to AKV)

    Note over CSI,AKV: CSI Driver acts on behalf of Pod

    Pod->>CSI: Request secret volume mount
    CSI->>AKV: GET secret (present Azure AD access token)
    AKV-->>CSI: Return secret value (authorised)
    CSI-->>Pod: Mount secret as in-memory tmpfs file

    Note over Pod: Pod reads secret from /mnt/secrets/. Secret never in env vars.
```

