## Diagram 5: Observability & Metric Data Flow (High-Level Design)

**Design Rationale:** This diagram cleanly separates the **log pipeline** (Fluent Bit → ELK/Splunk) from the **metrics pipeline** (Prometheus → Dynatrace). Both pipelines share the same egress path (ExpressRoute) but terminate at distinct on-premises consumers, which is accurately modelled here. Istio sidecars are shown as an intermediate enrichment stage for log metadata before Fluent Bit collection, matching the architecture where Istio generates access logs and telemetry consumed by the broader observability stack.

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph AKSCluster["AKS Cluster - newzealandnorth"]
        APP_PODS[Application Pods - ACI UPF Microservices]
        OP_PODS[Operator Pods - Istio / KEDA / cert-manager]
        SIDECARS[Istio Sidecars - Envoy Proxy]
        FLUENT[Fluent Bit DaemonSet]
        PROM[Prometheus Operator]
        NODE_METRICS[Node / kubelet Metrics]
    end

    subgraph EgressPath["Egress - ExpressRoute"]
        ER[ExpressRoute Circuit]
    end

    subgraph OnPremObservability["On-Premises Observability Stack"]
        ELK[ELK Stack - Log Analytics]
        SPLUNK[Splunk - Security / Audit Logs]
        DYNATRACE[Dynatrace - APM / Infrastructure]
    end

    APP_PODS -->|Stdout / Stderr Logs| SIDECARS
    OP_PODS -->|Stdout / Stderr Logs| FLUENT
    SIDECARS -->|Enriched Access Logs + Telemetry| FLUENT
    FLUENT -->|Forwarded Log Streams| ER

    NODE_METRICS -->|Scrape - kubelet / cAdvisor| PROM
    APP_PODS -->|Scrape - ServiceMonitor| PROM
    OP_PODS -->|Scrape - PodMonitor| PROM
    PROM -->|Remote Write / Metric Export| ER

    ER -->|Log Stream| ELK
    ER -->|Audit and Security Events| SPLUNK
    ER -->|Metrics and Traces| DYNATRACE
```
